 ğŸ§µ 1. Strings in Python

A string is a sequence of characters enclosed in quotes â€” single ('), double (") or triple (""").

âœ‚ï¸ String Slicing

You can extract parts of a string using slicing syntax:  
string[start:end:step]

ğŸ§° Common String Methods

| Method | Description | Example |
|--------|--------------|----------|
| upper() | Converts to uppercase | "hello".upper() â†’ "HELLO" |
| lower() | Converts to lowercase | "HELLO".lower() â†’ "hello" |
| title() | Capitalizes each word | "python basics".title() â†’ "Python Basics" |
| strip() | Removes whitespace | "  hi  ".strip() â†’ "hi" |
| replace(a, b) | Replaces text | "I love Java".replace("Java", "Python") â†’ "I love Python" |
| split() | Splits string into list | "a,b,c".split(",") â†’ ['a','b','c'] |
| find() | Finds index of substring | "python".find("t") â†’ 2 |



 ğŸ§º 2. Lists in Python

A list is an ordered, changeable collection of items.

ğŸ¯ Accessing List Elements
print(fruits[0])    # apple
print(fruits[-1])   # cherry
print(fruits[1:3])  # ['banana', 'cherry']

âš™ï¸ Common List Methods & Operations

| Method | Description | Example |
|--------|--------------|----------|
| append(x) | Add item at end | fruits.append("mango") |
| insert(i, x) | Insert item at position | fruits.insert(1, "grape") |
| remove(x) | Remove first matching value | fruits.remove("apple") |
| pop(i) | Remove by index | fruits.pop(1) |
| sort() | Sort list ascending | fruits.sort() |
| reverse() | Reverse order | fruits.reverse() |
| len(list) | Returns length | len(fruits) |
| list.extend(other) | Combine two lists | fruits.extend(["pear","melon"]) |
